segment.source: We offer two types of developer accounts: individual accounts, and company accounts.
segment.target: We offer two types of developer accounts: individual accounts, and company accounts.

segment.source: Developer accounts are offered in many countries and regions.

segment.source: We offer two types of developer accounts: individual accounts, and company accounts.
segment.target: We offer two types of developer accounts: individual accounts, and company accounts.

segment.source: Developer accounts are offered in many countries and regions.
segment.target: Developer accounts are offered in many countries and regions.

segment.source: Either type of account gives you access to publish apps to the Store and to participate in additional Microsoft developer programs.
segment.target: Either type of account gives you access to publish apps to the Store and to participate in additional Microsoft developer programs.

segment.source: Note Whether you create an account for a company or an individual, you can associate only one Microsoft account with the developer account.
segment.target: Note Whether you create an account for a company or an individual, you can associate only one Microsoft account with the developer account.

segment.source: When signing up for an account, make sure to sign in with the Microsoft account that you want to use for your developer account.
segment.target: When signing up for an account, make sure to sign in with the Microsoft account that you want to use for your developer account.

segment.source: When you begin the signup process you'll need to choose whether to create an individual account or a company account.
segment.target: When you begin the signup process you'll need to choose whether to create an individual account or a company account.

segment.source: Important You cannot change the account type once you make your selection, so be sure to choose the right type.
segment.target: Important You cannot change the account type once you make your selection, so be sure to choose the right type.

segment.source: Here are the essential differences between the two account types.
segment.target: Here are the essential differences between the two account types.

segment.source: Costs approximately $19 USD (the exact amount varies depending on your country or region)
segment.target: Costs approximately $19 USD (the exact amount varies depending on your country or region)

segment.source: Requires that your company is recognized as such in the country or region in which it is located

segment.source: Costs approximately $99 USD (the exact amount varies depending on your country or region)
segment.target: Costs approximately $99 USD (the exact amount varies depending on your country or region)

segment.source: Important If you decide to create a company account, be sure to review our guidelines for company accounts.
segment.target: Important If you decide to create a company account, be sure to review our guidelines for company accounts.

segment.source: Company accounts are a little more expensive, mostly because we take some additional steps to ensure that you are authorized to represent your company and set up the account.
segment.target: Company accounts are a little more expensive, mostly because we take some additional steps to ensure that you are authorized to represent your company and set up the account.

segment.source: One of the main benefits of having a company account is the ability to submit apps that declare additional App capability declarations.
segment.target: One of the main benefits of having a company account is the ability to submit apps that declare additional App capability declarations.

segment.source: Specifically, you must have a company account in order to publish apps that use the following three capabilities:
segment.target: Specifically, you must have a company account in order to publish apps that use the following three capabilities:

segment.source: enterpriseAuthentication—Uses Windows credentials for access to a corporate intranet.
segment.target: enterpriseAuthentication—Uses Windows credentials for access to a corporate intranet.

segment.source: This is typically used in line-of-business apps that connect to servers within an enterprise.
segment.target: This is typically used in line-of-business apps that connect to servers within an enterprise.

segment.source: (You don't need this capability for generic communication across the internet.)
segment.target: (You don't need this capability for generic communication across the internet.)

segment.source: sharedUserCertificates—Enables an app to access software and hardware certificates, such as certificates stored on a smart card.
segment.target: sharedUserCertificates—Enables an app to access software and hardware certificates, such as certificates stored on a smart card.

segment.source: This is typically used for financial or enterprise apps that require a smart card for authentication.
segment.target: This is typically used for financial or enterprise apps that require a smart card for authentication.

segment.source: documentsLibrary—Allows programmatic access to the user's Documents, filtered to the file type associations declared in the package manifest.
segment.target: documentsLibrary—Allows programmatic access to the user's Documents, filtered to the file type associations declared in the package manifest.

segment.source: (You don't need to declare this capability in order to access a user's Documents with the file picker).
segment.target: (You don't need to declare this capability in order to access a user's Documents with the file picker).

segment.source: Note that apps targeting Windows Phone 8.1 or earlier cannot use the documentsLibrary capability.
segment.target: Note that apps targeting Windows Phone 8.1 or earlier cannot use the documentsLibrary capability.

segment.source: Note In addition, you must contact support and get approval before you can submit apps that declare the documentsLibrary capability.
segment.target: Note In addition, you must contact support and get approval before you can submit apps that declare the documentsLibrary capability.

segment.source: Having a company account does not guarantee that apps using these capabilities will pass certification.
segment.target: Having a company account does not guarantee that apps using these capabilities will pass certification.

segment.source: These capabilities are intended for very specific scenarios, and most apps shouldn't declare them.
segment.target: These capabilities are intended for very specific scenarios, and most apps shouldn't declare them.

segment.source: For more information, see App capability declarations.
segment.target: For more information, see App capability declarations.

segment.source: For company accounts, we use Symantec to verify that you’re authorized to create an account for the company that you’re representing.
segment.target: For company accounts, we use Symantec to verify that you’re authorized to create an account for the company that you’re representing.

segment.source: This process can take from a few days to a couple of weeks, and often includes a phone call to your company (so make sure your contact information is up to date when you fill out the registration forms).
segment.target: This process can take from a few days to a couple of weeks, and often includes a phone call to your company (so make sure your contact information is up to date when you fill out the registration forms).

segment.source: You can't submit apps from a company account until it's been verified, but while you're waiting, you can reserve an app name, access your Windows Dev Center dashboard, and continue building and testing your app.
segment.target: You can't submit apps from a company account until it's been verified, but while you're waiting, you can reserve an app name, access your Windows Dev Center dashboard, and continue building and testing your app.
